[
  {
    "startTime": 0.4,
    "endTime": 3.5,
    "text": "Fancy a cuppa?"
  },
  {
    "startTime": 3.5,
    "endTime": 11.0,
    "text": "If you would like to offer someone a cup of tea, you can say \"fancy a cuppa?\""
  },
  {
    "startTime": 11.0,
    "endTime": 17.5,
    "text": "'Fancy...?' is a shortened form of 'do you fancy' and means 'do you want?'"
  },
  {
    "startTime": 17.5,
    "endTime": 19.0,
    "text": "For example,"
  },
  {
    "startTime": 19.0,
    "endTime": 21.8,
    "text": "Fancy a chat?"
  },
  {
    "startTime": 21.8,
    "endTime": 24.0,
    "text": "Fancy a beer?"
  },
  {
    "startTime": 24.0,
    "endTime": 27.5,
    "text": "Fancy a film?"
  },
  {
    "startTime": 27.5,
    "endTime": 32.26,
    "text": "'A cuppa' is the way we pronounce 'a cup of' in spoken english."
  },
  {
    "startTime": 33.94,
    "endTime": 40.66,
    "text": "When we say a cuppa, we use a schwa sound at the start and end."
  },
  {
    "startTime": 41.84,
    "endTime": 45.0,
    "text": "A cup of coffee."
  },
  {
    "startTime": 45.0,
    "endTime": 47.24,
    "text": "A cup of hot chocolate."
  },
  {
    "startTime": 47.24,
    "endTime": 48.160000000000004,
    "text": "A cup of tea."
  },
  {
    "startTime": 50.94,
    "endTime": 60.449999999999996,
    "text": "In addition to saying a cuppa instead of a cup of in spoken english, we can also use a cuppa as a noun meaning 'a cup of tea'."
  },
  {
    "startTime": 61.14,
    "endTime": 65.61,
    "text": "So, \"fancy a cuppa?\" means \"do you want a cup of tea?\""
  },
  {
    "startTime": 68.24,
    "endTime": 72.0,
    "text": "Fancy a cuppa, anyone?"
  },
  {
    "startTime": 72.0,
    "endTime": 75.96,
    "text": "That was bbclearningenglish.com"
  }
]